&gt; 
&gt; &gt; (1) Is there a better way?
&gt; &gt; (2) Will the variables defined in oneTimeSetup be in scope 
&gt; inside MyTest?
&gt; &gt; (3) How can I reuse the fixture defined in this class for 
&gt; another set of
&gt; &gt; tests?
&gt; &gt; (4) Will the fixtures defined the suite&#39;s TestCase&#39;s still 
&gt; be created?
&gt; 
&gt; 1) Yes, comment your code ;)  Seriously, a better way to 
&gt; what?  What is it
&gt; that you seek to accomplish?  If, as the name AllTests 
&gt; implies, this test is
&gt; simply plumbing to run all of your tests, then you don&#39;t need 
&gt; a fixture.
&gt; You can remove the TestSuite wrapper and the oneTimeSetUp and
&gt; oneTimeTearDown methods.  Simply have your suite() method return the
&gt; TestSuite to which you have added your tests, not the 
&gt; TestSetup wrapper.
&gt; 2) Variables declared in a method are scoped to that method, 
&gt; so they are out
&gt; of scope outside of the method.  Class that inherit from the 
&gt; class in which
&gt; your (public or protected) method is defined have acces to 
&gt; the method (and
&gt; therefore the effects of the variable), but the variable is 
&gt; still scoped to
&gt; the method and not beyond.
&gt; 3) If you remove the TestSetup wrapper, then you won&#39;t have a 
&gt; fixture to
&gt; reuse in other classes.  At my company, I created a zTestCase 
&gt; class that
&gt; extends TestCase.  In my class, I define a generic fixture, 
&gt; and provide
&gt; convenience methods for manipulating that fixture.  All of 
&gt; our tests (all
&gt; those that need the fixture) extend zTestCase.  That way, our 
&gt; tests leverage
&gt; the fixture in their supers, and override oneTimeSetUp if 
&gt; they need to alter
&gt; the generic fixture.
&gt; 4) Yes, unless their oneTimeSetUp overrides the setUp method, 
&gt; in which case,
&gt; no.  Again, it depends on what you seek to accomplish.
&gt; 
&gt; Hope that helps,
&gt; 
&gt; _chas_
